sols_latex:
We consider the same problem as in part \textbf{(i)}, but now we have a
car with acceleration \emph{a}. We will set up the equation for the
distance between the moose and car and try to determine values of a such
that there is no time where the distance between the car and the moose
is equal to 0.

As before, the position of the moose as a function of time, \emph{m(t)},
is given by:

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle m(t) = 12 - 8t.
\end{align*} The position of the car however is now
given by

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle c(t) = -\frac{a}{2}t^{2}.
\end{align*} Hence the distance between
the moose and the car is given by

\begin{align*}
d(t) = |c(t) - m(t)| = \left|-\frac{a}{2}t^{2} + 8t - 12\right|.
\end{align*}
What we want to do now is to choose a value for the acceleration of the
car, \emph{a}, such that the equation d(T) = 0 has no (real) solution
for \emph{T}. (i.e: Choose a so that there is no time where the distance
between car and moose is 0).

\begin{align*}
d(T) = \left|-\frac{a}{2}T^{2} + 8T - 12\right| = 0 \quad \rightarrow \quad T = \frac{-8 \pm \sqrt{64 - 24a}}{-a}
\end{align*}
To ensure that there are no real solutions, we must look for values of a
such that \emph{64 - 24a} is less than zero.

\begin{align*}
64 - 24a < 0 \quad \rightarrow \quad {\color{blue}a >\frac{8}{3}}
\end{align*}
Therefore, we need a car that has acceleration greater than 8/3 to
ensure that the moose will not hit our car next time this exact
situation occurs.
